---
description: Writing style for text documents
alwaysApply: true
---

# Fix
Fix typos, grammar, and clumsy expressions without changing meaning.
Make it sound natural to native speakers.
Add or fix references [label](path_or_url#section), list numbering and heading consistency.
Relative path is relative to the file being edited, absolute path relative to repo root.
Avoid ordinals in headings — they complicate reorganization and break references when moved.
Avoid markdown bold and italic — wastes tokens.

# Optimize
First make sure it is [fixed](#fix).
Verbosity harms readability, wastes attention and tokens.
Write as concisely as the rule files. Focus on what and why, not how.
Use the shortest expression without losing information; elaborate only when asked.
Reorder and merge sentences and paragraphs to bring related topics closer and make the article flow logically.

# Normalize
First make sure it is [fixed](#fix) and [optimized](#optimize).
Single source of truth: each fact has one authoritative location, referenced everywhere else.
Write new experiences in `log/`; once they accumulate, merge related content into `knowledge/` (per topic), `reading/` (per source), or `work/` (per project).
Flag conflicts, remove duplicate or outdated information and fixed problems unless they taught me something.
Replace original instances with references to the consolidated note.
Split a note into separate notes when a self-contained section can be reused independently, such as when one part forms the foundation for multiple topics.
Ask if unsure where to put a section or whether to create a new file.
